<subsection xml:id="subsec-surface-area-of-pyramids" xmlns:xi="http://www.w3.org/2001/XInclude">
    <title>Surface Area of Pyramids</title>
    <objectives component="outcomes">
        <introduction xml:id="auto_kkv9ev5h">
            <dl>
                <li xml:id="auto_oqbpq5oz">
                    <title>Strand</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_va9avgyf">
                        2.0 Measurements and Geometry
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_izxnuo5a">
                    <title>Sub-Strand</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_w17qi5h5">
                        2.7 Surface Area
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_8dbmhud5">
                    <title>Specific Learning Outcomes</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_86c7vd3x">
                        Determine the surface area of prisms, pyramids, cones, frustums and spheres
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_hi6pj70w" component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Grade Level</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_cwsdab6s">
                        10
                    </p>
                </li>
                <li xml:id="auto_9vw1kabt" component="lesson-plan">
                    <title>Estimated Duration</title>
                    <p xml:id="auto_0nfcipxb">
                        40 minutes
                    </p>
                </li>
            </dl>
            <p xml:id="auto_qo6jf4ub" component="lesson-plan">
                <p xml:id="auto_nkqti39u"> Upon completion of this lesson, learners will be able to:
                <ol>
                    <li xml:id="auto_tr1igpce">
                        <p xml:id="auto_fh677mfv">
                            <alert>Know (Conceptual Understanding):</alert> Understand the definition of a pyramid, the difference between a pyramid and a prism, and the relationship between the base and triangular faces.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_b901ow7x">
                        <p xml:id="auto_uwk8qh79">
                            <alert>Do (Procedural Skill):</alert> Apply the formula <m>\text{Surface Area} = \text{Base Area} + \text{Sum of all triangular face areas}</m> to calculate the surface area of pyramids.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                    <li xml:id="auto_brsyzyv9">
                        <p xml:id="auto_5e6ydjmi">
                            <alert>Apply (Application/Problem-Solving):</alert> Solve real-life problems involving the surface area of pyramids, including architectural and packaging contexts.
                        </p>
                    </li>
                </ol>
                </p>
            </p>
        </introduction>
        <ul>
            <li xml:id="auto_gi5kqobq">Determine the surface area of prisms, pyramids, cones, frustums and spheres</li>
            <li xml:id="auto_22jxxhkw">Explore the use of the surface area and volume of solids in real-life situations</li>
        </ul>
    </objectives>
        <axiom component="resources">
        <!-- Link to blurb -->
        <xi:include href="../../resources-blurb-lesson.ptx" />

        <sbsgroup widths="45% 45%" margins="2% 2%">
            <sidebyside>
                <p xml:id="auto_fdm2zfsi">
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/measurements-and-geometry/surface-area/surface-area-of-pyramids.pdf"> Lesson Plan </dataurl>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_jmufcstx">
                    <dataurl source="lesson_plans/measurements-and-geometry/surface-area/step-by-step-guide_surface-area-of-pyramids.pdf"> Step-by-Step Guide </dataurl>
                </p>
            </sidebyside>
        </sbsgroup>
    </axiom>
    <xi:include href="../../resources-materials.ptx" />

    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Problem-Solving and Discovery</title>
        <dl>
            <li xml:id="auto_481hph0a">
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_e5b09blu">
                    15 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_ob61rkn6">
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_k2edhykc">
                    Students discover the formula for finding the surface area of a pyramid by constructing a pyramid net from paper and exploring the relationship between the base and triangular faces.
                </p>
            </li>
        </dl>
        <paragraphs>
            <title>Teacher's Role</title>
            <p xml:id="auto_vqqzg7li">
                Circulate among groups, ensuring students understand how to draw and cut the pyramid net accurately. Ask probing questions:
            </p>
            <ul>
                <li xml:id="auto_mk7fc09k"><p xml:id="auto_otayane5">What shapes do you see in the net?</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_zz8lbn5h"><p xml:id="auto_4slehkar">How can we find the area of each shape?</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_p59e5vxm"><p xml:id="auto_p63a2jpu">How many faces does your pyramid have?</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_3wlxp91n"><p xml:id="auto_i0q5exsu">What is the difference between the base and the lateral faces?</p></li>
            </ul>
            <p xml:id="auto_bjpbibe6">
                For struggling groups: <q>Let us find the area of the base first. Then find the area of each triangular face. What do we do next?</q>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_egnjc0pb">
                For early finishers: <q>Can you write a general formula for finding the surface area of any pyramid?</q>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_3ulurj20">
                Guide students to articulate: The surface area of a pyramid equals the base area plus the sum of all triangular face areas. Identify 2–3 groups with clear findings to share with the class.
            </p>
        </paragraphs>
        <paragraphs>
            <title>Discussion Prompts</title>
            <ul>
                <li xml:id="auto_hv75v8qj"><p xml:id="auto_7w8e8bcz">What is a pyramid?</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_erpjsldr"><p xml:id="auto_vruws7pq">What shapes make up the net of a pyramid?</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_rcut232k"><p xml:id="auto_gj16rl8z">How did you calculate the surface area of the pyramid?</p></li>
            </ul>
        </paragraphs>
    </axiom>


        
           <activity xml:id="auto_xbno6jyp">
         <title>Net of a triangle based Pyramid</title> 
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_wfzclfbl">
                    
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_zkwzlp4o">
                   Paper Folding to form a Pyramid. 
                </p>
                <image>
                <latex-image>
                 \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1, every node/.style={font=\small}]
                    \definecolor{lightblue}{RGB}{173,216,230}

                    % Net 1
                    \begin{scope}
                    % Base triangle
                    \filldraw[fill=lightblue, draw=black] (0,0) -- (2,0) -- (1,1.732) -- cycle;

                    % Left triangle
                    \filldraw[fill=lightblue, draw=black] (0,0) -- (-1,1.732) -- (1,1.732) -- cycle;

                    % Right triangle
                    \filldraw[fill=lightblue, draw=black] (2,0) -- (3,1.732) -- (1,1.732) -- cycle;

                    % Top triangle
                    \filldraw[fill=lightblue, draw=black] (1,1.732) -- (1,3.464) -- (3,1.732) -- cycle;

                    \node at (1,-1) {Net 1};
                    \end{scope}

                    % Net 2
                    \begin{scope}[xshift=3.5cm]
                    % Four triangles in a row
                    \foreach \i in {0,1,2,3} {
                    \filldraw[fill=lightblue, draw=black] 
                        ({\i*2},0) -- ({\i*2+1},1.732) -- ({\i*2+2},0) -- cycle;
                    }
                    \node at (4,-1) {Net 2};
                    \end{scope}

                    % Arrow
                    \draw[thick, -&gt;] (6.5,2) -- (10.5,2) node[midway, above] {folds to};

                    % 3D Triangular Pyramid (Tetrahedron)
                    \begin{scope}[xshift=13cm, yshift=0.5cm]
                    % Base triangle
                    \filldraw[fill=lightblue, draw=black] (0,0) -- (2,0) -- (1,1.732) -- cycle;
                    % Side triangle (left)
                    \draw[fill=lightblue, draw=black] (0,0) -- (1,1.732) -- (1,3) -- cycle;
                    % Side triangle (right)
                    \draw[fill=lightblue, draw=black] (2,0) -- (1,1.732) -- (1,3) -- cycle;
                    % Hidden edges
                    \draw[dashed] (1,3) -- (0,0);
                    \draw[dashed] (1,3) -- (2,0);

                    \node at (0.5,-1) {Triangular Pyramid};
                    \end{scope}

                \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
                </image>
                <p xml:id="auto_wydt6wab">
                    Materials Needed.
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_k3d62d34">
                    <ul xml:id="auto_qc8nd5f3" marker="disc">
                        <li xml:id="auto_tpukkuie">
                            <p xml:id="auto_lesgv6oz">
                                Colored paper or cardstocks
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_a7l628vb">
                            <p xml:id="auto_qm2497jq">
                               Scissors 
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_lzz1znd5">
                            <p xml:id="auto_g2pdqmlp">
                               Rulers 
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_y1odfor1">
                            <p xml:id="auto_lbzvk7cc">
                               Glue or tape 
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_9q5u2uf3">
                            <p xml:id="auto_9qudf4vn">
                                Markers
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_wpxc5oe8">
                    
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_a8qu5yw4">
                    <ul xml:id="auto_zfcqx068">
                        <li xml:id="auto_0d7znfqk">
                            <p xml:id="auto_kx4d49p0">
                                Steps.
                            </p>
                            <p xml:id="auto_3asm14g5">
                               ♦ Observe the net of the pyramid shown above.
                            </p>
                            <p xml:id="auto_wg43gi7h">
                              ♦  Draw on the Colored paper or cardstocks the net of a pyramid that is, four triangles. Note the sides of the triangles and height should be equal.
                            </p>
                            <p xml:id="auto_39t6wko9">
                             ♦ Cut off the extra paper to remain with the pyramid net.
                            </p>  
                            <p xml:id="auto_rsx1nman">
                              ♦  Fold along the edges to form a pyramid. Hold the triangles in position using a tape.
                            </p>
                            <p xml:id="auto_lp4qrki0">
                              ♦  Using a ruler, measure the base height and slant height of the triangular faces.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                        <li xml:id="auto_vhaxrpno">
                            <p xml:id="auto_7t44i08e">
                                Find the volume of the pyramid you have constructed.
                            </p>
                        </li>
                    </ul>
                </p>
            </statement>
        </activity>
        <activity xml:id="auto_ei38sx0n">
        <title>Observing pyramidal objects in the surrounding environment</title>
        
              
            <statement>
                <sidebyside>
                     <p xml:id="auto_lvptxpl3">
                        <ul xml:id="auto_ml7d0fgo">
                            <li xml:id="auto_00nijf0r">
                                <p xml:id="auto_3bsgfpf3">
                                    
                                </p>
                                <p xml:id="auto_qard57d2">
                                ♦ Identify pyramid-shaped objects around school/home e.g., tent(Shown alongside), roof, food container, toys etc.
                            </p>
                            <p xml:id="auto_66fkc4qz">
                                ♦ Measure dimensions or use estimated values.
                            </p>
                            <p xml:id="auto_5r5qja5z">
                            ♦ Find their surface area using the formula and compare with classmates.
                            </p>
                            </li>
                        </ul>
                        </p>
                <image>
                <latex-image label="tent-image">
                    \begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1.2]

                            %
                            % Define color
                            \definecolor{tentgreen}{RGB}{102,153,102}

                            % Coordinates for pyramid base
                            \coordinate (A) at (0,0);
                            \coordinate (B) at (4,0);
                            \coordinate (C) at (1.5,-1.5);
                            \coordinate (O) at (2,2.5); % Apex

                            % Base triangle
                            \filldraw[fill=tentgreen!60, draw=black] (A) -- (B) -- (C) -- cycle;

                            % Left face
                            \filldraw[fill=tentgreen!80, draw=black] (A) -- (C) -- (O) -- cycle;

                            % Right face
                            \filldraw[fill=tentgreen!80!black, draw=black] (B) -- (C) -- (O) -- cycle;

                            % Front face (flap)
                            \filldraw[fill=tentgreen!70, draw=black] (A) -- (B) -- (O) -- cycle;

                            % Ropes and pegs
                            \draw[black] (A) -- (-0.7,-0.7);
                            \filldraw[black] (-0.7,-0.7) circle (1pt);
                            \draw[black] (B) -- (4.7,-0.7);
                            \filldraw[black] (4.7,-0.7) circle (1pt);

                            % Ground line
                            \draw[thick, brown!60!black] (-1,0) -- (5,0);
                        
                    \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
                </image>
                </sidebyside>
                
            </statement>
        </activity>
<axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Structured Instruction</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_uonnoolm">
            <dl>
            <li xml:id="auto_5dtb62qj">
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_gt3xap88">
                    10 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_80fdfxba">
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_gx0hshd5">
                    To formalize the pyramid surface area formula and address common misconceptions about pyramids vs. prisms.
                </p>
            </li>
            </dl>
        </p>
        <paragraphs>
            <title>Scaffolding Strategies</title>
            <ul>
                <li xml:id="auto_29zgrc85"><p xml:id="auto_qz79mlrx"><alert>Misconception:</alert> A pyramid is the same as a prism. <alert>Clarification:</alert> A pyramid has triangular faces that meet at an apex, while a prism has rectangular faces and two parallel bases.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_sh52y9vf"><p xml:id="auto_k5ebncdh"><alert>Misconception:</alert> I only need to find the area of the triangular faces. <alert>Clarification:</alert> You must add the base area to the sum of all triangular face areas.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_11bl1m8l"><p xml:id="auto_gwx92aax"><alert>Misconception:</alert> All pyramids have square bases. <alert>Clarification:</alert> Pyramids can have triangular, square, rectangular, or any polygonal base.</p></li>
                <li xml:id="auto_5dwaw2sq"><p xml:id="auto_uy79va8d"><alert>Misconception:</alert> The height and slant height are the same. <alert>Clarification:</alert> The slant height is the distance along the triangular face from the apex to the base edge, while the height is the perpendicular distance from the apex to the base.</p></li>
            </ul>
        </paragraphs>
    </axiom>

        <insight xml:id="auto_5fhhpw1j">
            <p xml:id="auto_44xungt3">
                A <m>\text{pyramid}</m> is a geometric solid object that has a polygon as its base and faces that converge at a point called the apex.
                In other words the faces are not perpendicular to the base
            </p> 
            <p xml:id="auto_zdpf5vay">
                The polygons that can act as the face of the pyramids include:         </p>   
            <p xml:id="auto_7it8vq7x">
            🔹  Triangle: Thus called  triangular pyramid.
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_nx3xdxdc">
            🔹  Squares: Thus called  square pyramid.
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_o3zpp39w">
            🔹The two pyramids take their names after the shape of their base.
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_db1bdg6k"> 
                A right pyramid's line between the apex and the centre of the base is perpendicular to the base.
            </p>
        </insight>

