    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Practice and Application</title>
        <p xml:id="auto_z9t7yoxv">
            <dl>
            <li xml:id="auto_t1m0x8pz">
                <title>Suggested Time</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_rp91ybs1">
                    10 minutes
                </p>
            </li>
            <li xml:id="auto_pid2ws8d">
                <title>Objective</title>
                <p xml:id="auto_3l5lwtwm">
                    Provide varied problems involving pyramids with different base shapes, requiring reasoning and application of the surface area formula.
                </p>
            </li>
            </dl>
        </p>
        <paragraphs>
            <title>Teacher Guidance</title>
            <p xml:id="auto_4q2hxnlp">
                Work through the first example (triangular pyramid using Heron's formula) with the class. Then allow students to attempt the remaining examples individually or in pairs. Circulate to check that students are correctly identifying base area and triangular face areas.
            </p>
        </paragraphs>
    </axiom>

         
        
        <example xml:id="auto_3xjbjdf1">
            <statement>
                <p xml:id="auto_f6ceswf9">
                    Find the surface area of the following triangular pyramid (correct to 1 d.p)
                </p>
                <image width="70%">
                <latex-image label="triangle-pyramid">
                    \begin{tikzpicture}
                             % Define vertices
                                  \coordinate (A) at (0, 0);
                                    \coordinate (B) at (4, 0);
                                    \coordinate (C) at (2, 3);
                                    \coordinate (D) at (2, 1.5);

                                    % Draw edges of the triangular pyramid
                                    \draw[thick] (A) -- (B) -- (C) -- cycle; % Base triangle
                                    \draw[thick] (A) -- (D);
                                    \draw[thick] (B) -- (D);
                                    \draw[thick] (C) -- (D);

                                    % Dashed lines for hidden edges
                                    \draw[dashed] (D) -- (A);

                                    % Label vertices
                                    \node[left] at (A) {A};
                                    \node[right] at (B) {B};
                                    \node[above] at (C) {C};
                                    \node[below] at (D) {D};

                                    % Label side lengths
                                    \node[below] at (2, 0) { 4 cm};
                                    \node[above left,rotate=50] at (1.2, 1.8) {3 cm};
                                    \node[above right,rotate=-30] at (2.5, 0.9) {7 cm};
                                    \node[left,rotate=45] at (1.7, 1.7) {6 cm};
                                    \node[right] at (3, 1.5) {  5 cm};
                                    \node[right,rotate=90] at (1.8, 1.6) {6 cm};
                            \end{tikzpicture}
                </latex-image>
                </image>
            </statement>
            <solution>
                <p xml:id="auto_2h6ai1cx">
                    The surface area of a triangular pyramid is the sum of the areas of all <m>\textbf{four triangular faces}</m>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_ucp5blcs">
                    In finding the surface area we need to recall the definations of a net and a prism.
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_9e1ip718">
                    The net of a pyramid consists of a base triangle <m>ABC</m>, which is a polygon that represents the base of the pyramid, and triangular faces<m> \angle \, ABD,\, \angle \, BCD, \, \angle ACD</m> that represent the sides of the pyramid.
                    </p>
                    <p xml:id="auto_z94j8069">
                        Each triangle's area will be found using Heron’s Formula:
                <md>
                    <mrow>  A =\amp \sqrt{S(S-a)(S-b)(S-c)} </mrow>
                </md>
                Where <m>S</m> is the semi perimeter.
                <md>
                    <mrow> S = \amp \frac{a+b+c}{2} </mrow>
                </md>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_ghnjvod9">
                    Find the Area of the Base Triangle <m>ABC</m>. Given sides <m>AB = 4\, \text{cm}, \, BC = 5\, \text{cm} , \,AC = 3\, \text{cm}</m>
                </p>
                <p xml:id="auto_vd7clmyf">
                    Calculate the semi-perimeter:
                    <md>
                        <mrow> S = \amp \frac{4\, \text{cm}+5\, \text{cm}+3\, \text{cm}}{2} = 6 \, \text{cm} </mrow>
                        
                    </md>
                    Apply Heron’s Formula:
                    <md>
                        <mrow>A_{ABC} = \amp  \sqrt{6(6-4)(6-5)(6-3)}  </mrow>
                        <mrow> = \amp \sqrt{6 \times(2)\times(1)\times(3)} </mrow>
                        <mrow> = \amp \sqrt{36} </mrow>

                        <mrow> = \amp 6 \, \text{cm}^2 </mrow>
                    </md>
                    Find the Area of Side Triangle<m> ABD</m> Given sides <m>AB = 4\, \text{cm}, \, AD = 6\, \text{cm} , \, BD = 7\, \text{cm} </m>
                    <md>
                    <mrow> S = \amp \frac{4 \,\text{cm}+6\, \text{cm}+7\, \text{cm}}{2} =  8.5 \, \text{cm} </mrow>
                        <mrow>A_{ABD} = \amp  \sqrt{8.5(8.5-4)(8.5-6)(8.5-7)}  </mrow>
                        <mrow> = \amp \sqrt{8.5 \times(4.5)\times(2.5)\times(1.5)} </mrow>
                        <mrow> = \amp \sqrt{143.44} </mrow>

                        <mrow> = \amp 11.97 \, \text{cm}^2</mrow>
                    </md>
                    Find the Area of Side Triangle<m> BCD</m> Given sides <m>BC = 5, \, \text{cm} \,CD = 6 , \, \text{cm} \, BD = 7 \text{cm}</m>
                    <md>
                    <mrow> S = \amp \frac{5 \, \text{cm}+6 \, \text{cm}+7 \, \text{cm}}{2} =  9 \, \text{cm} </mrow>
                        <mrow>A_{BCD} = \amp  \sqrt{9(9-4)(9-6)(9-7)}  </mrow>
                        <mrow> = \amp \sqrt{9 \times(4)\times(2)\times(3)} </mrow>
                        <mrow> = \amp \sqrt{216} </mrow>

                        <mrow> = \amp 14.7  \, \text{cm}^2</mrow>
                    </md>
                    Find the Area of Side Triangle<m> ACD</m> Given sides <m>AC = 3, \, AD = 6 , \, CD = 6 </m>
                    <md>
                        <mrow> S = \amp \frac{3 \, \text{cm}+6 \, \text{cm}+6 \, \text{cm}}{2} =  7.5 \, \text{cm} </mrow>
                        <mrow>A_{ACD} = \amp  \sqrt{7.5(7.5-4)(7.5-6)(7.5-7)}  </mrow>
                        <mrow> = \amp \sqrt{7.5 \times(4.5)\times(1.5)\times(1.5)} </mrow>
                        <mrow> = \amp \sqrt{75.94} </mrow>

                        <mrow> = \amp 8.71\, \text{cm}^2</mrow>
                    </md>
                    Find the Total Surface Area.
                    Surface Area = <m>A_{ABC} + A_{ABD} +A_{BCD} + A_{ACD}</m>
                    <md>
                    <mrow>=  \amp 6  \, \text{cm}^2 + 11.97   \, \text{cm}^2 + 14.7  \, \text{cm}^2 + 8.71  \, \text{cm}^2 </mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp 41.38  \, \text{cm}^2</mrow>
                    </md>
                </p>
            </solution>
        </example>
        
       <example xml:id="auto_gh11tpag">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_812nlcvy">
                Draw the net of the pyramid.
            </p>
          <sidebyside>
            <image>
            <shortdescription> Net of square pyramid</shortdescription>
                
            <latex-image label="net-square-pyramid">
                \begin{tikzpicture}
                                 
                % Define the coordinates of the rectangular base (4 cm × 2 cm)
                    \coordinate (A) at (0,0);
                    \coordinate (B) at (4,0);
                    \coordinate (C) at (4,2);
                    \coordinate (D) at (0,2);
                    
                    % Define the peak (apex) of the pyramid
                    \coordinate (P) at (2,4);  % Centered above the rectangle

                    % Fill the shapes with different colors
                    \fill[cyan!60] (A) -- (B) -- (C) -- (D) -- cycle;

                    % Draw the outlines of the pyramid
                    \draw[thick] (A) -- (B) -- (C) -- (D) -- cycle; % Base rectangle
                    \draw[thick] (A) -- (P) -- (B); % Front triangle
                    \draw[thick] (B) -- (P) -- (C); % Right triangle
                    \draw[thick] (C) -- (P) -- (D); % Back triangle
                    \draw[thick] (D) -- (P) -- (A); % Left triangle

                    % Add dashed fold lines
                    \draw[dashed] (A) -- (P);
                    \draw[dashed] (B) -- (P);
                    \draw[dashed] (C) -- (P);
                    \draw[dashed] (D) -- (P);

                    % Label the points
                    \node[below left] at (A) {A};
                    \node[below right] at (B) {B};
                    \node[above right] at (C) {C};
                    \node[above left] at (D) {D};
                    \node[above] at (P) {P};
                    \node at (0,-1){ Rectangular Pyramid};
                \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
            </image>
            <image>
            <shortdescription>Square pyramid</shortdescription>
            <latex-image label="square-pyramid-net">
                \begin{tikzpicture}
                    % Define colors
                    \definecolor{basecolor}{RGB}{135, 206, 250}  % Gold for the base
                    \definecolor{facecolor}{RGB}{135, 206, 255} % Light blue for the triangular faces

                    % Base (square)
                    \fill[basecolor] (2,2) -- (4,4) -- (2,6) -- (0,4) -- cycle;  (D) -- (A) -- (P) -- cycle; % Left triangle

                   

                    % Base outline
                    \draw[thick] (2,2) -- (4,4) -- (2,6) -- (0,4) -- cycle;

                    % Triangular faces outline
                    \draw[thick] (2,6) -- (2,8) -- (4,4);
                    \draw[thick] (4,4) -- (2,8) -- (2,2);
                    \draw[thick] (2,2) -- (2,8) -- (0,4);
                    \draw[thick] (0,4) -- (2,8) -- (2,6);
                    \node at (1,1.5){ Square Pyramid};
                \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
            </image>
          </sidebyside>
        </statement>

        <solution>
            <p xml:id="auto_tazv5zj5">
                The net of the pyramid is shown below.
            </p>

            <image>
            <latex-image label="triangular-prism-one">
                \begin{tikzpicture}
                                    % Define colors
                    \definecolor{basecolor}{RGB}{255, 165, 0}  % Orange (Base)
                    \definecolor{facecolor}{RGB}{135, 206, 250} % Light Blue (Faces)

                    % Draw the base (square)
                    \fill[basecolor] (0,0) -- (4,0) -- (4,4) -- (0,4) -- cycle;
                    \draw (0,0) -- (4,0) -- (4,4) -- (0,4) -- cycle;
                    \fill[facecolor](0,0) --(2,-3) --(4,0) -- cycle;
                    \fill[facecolor](4,0) --(7,2) --(4,4)-- cycle;
                    \fill[facecolor](0,4) --(2,7) --(4,4) -- cycle;
                    \fill[facecolor] (0,0) --(-3,2) --(0,4) -- cycle;
                    
                    % Draw triangle outlines
                    \draw (0,0) -- (2,-3) -- (4,0) -- cycle;
                    \draw (4,0) -- (7,2) -- (4,4) -- cycle;
                    \draw (0,4) -- (2,7) -- (4,4) -- cycle;
                    \draw (0,0) -- (-3,2) -- (0,4) -- cycle;

                    % Label the pyramid net
                    \node at (2,2) {\textbf{Base}};
                    \node at (2,-1.5) {\textbf{Face}};
                    \node at (5.5,2) {\textbf{Face}};
                    \node at (-1.5,2) {\textbf{Face}};
                    \node at (2,4.5) {\textbf{Face}};
                \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
                <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                
            </image>
        </solution>
       </example>

        <p xml:id="auto_5fqmiy7e">
         The surface area of a pyramid is the total area of the lateral faces and the base of the pyramid.
       </p>

    <example xml:id="auto_ek0sygyb">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_15sa81ve">
                Calculate the surface area of a pyramid whose base is rectangular and slant height <m>6</m><m>\text{cm}</m> as shown below.
            </p>

            <image width="50%">
            <latex-image label="triangular-prism-two">
                \begin{tikzpicture}
                            
                % Define the coordinates of the rectangular base (4 cm × 2 cm)
                    \coordinate (A) at (0,0);
                    \coordinate (B) at (4,0);
                    \coordinate (C) at (4,2);
                    \coordinate (D) at (0,2);
                    
                    % Define the peak (apex) of the pyramid
                    \coordinate (P) at (2,4);  % Centered above the rectangle

                    % Fill the shapes with different colors
                    \fill[cyan!60] (A) -- (B) -- (C) -- (D) -- cycle; % Base rectangle
                   
                    % Draw the outlines of the pyramid
                    \draw[thick] (A) -- (B) -- (C) -- (D) -- cycle; % Base rectangle
                    \draw[thick] (A) -- (P) -- (B); % Front triangle
                    \draw[thick] (B) -- (P) -- (C); % Right triangle
                    \draw[thick] (C) -- (P) -- (D); % Back triangle
                    \draw[thick] (D) -- (P) -- (A); % Left triangle

                    % Add dashed fold lines
                    \draw[dashed] (A) -- (P);
                    \draw[dashed] (B) -- (P);
                    \draw[dashed] (C) -- (P);
                    \draw[dashed] (D) -- (P);

                    % Label the points
                    \node[below left] at (A) {A};
                    \node[below right] at (B) {B};
                    \node[above right] at (C) {C};
                    \node[above left] at (D) {D};
                    \node[above] at (P) {P};
                \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
                <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                
            </image>
        </statement>

        <solution>
            <p xml:id="auto_uuba9fbp">
                 <m>\text{First we form the net of the pyramid.}</m>
            </p>

            <image >
            <latex-image label="triangular-prism-three">
                \begin{tikzpicture}
                                 % Define the coordinates of the main rectangle (5 cm × 3 cm)
                    \coordinate (A) at (0,0);
                    \coordinate (B) at (5,0);
                    \coordinate (C) at (5,3);
                    \coordinate (D) at (0,3);

                    % Define the coordinates of the outer triangles (adjusted for consistency)
                    \coordinate (V1) at (2.5,6);  % Top triangle peak
                    \coordinate (V2) at (8,1.5);  % Right triangle peak
                    \coordinate (V3) at (2.5,-3); % Bottom triangle peak
                    \coordinate (V4) at (-3,1.5); % Left triangle peak

                    % Draw and fill the shapes with different colors
                    \fill[cyan!60] (A) -- (B) -- (C) -- (D) -- cycle; % Rectangle (grayish)
                   
                    % Draw the outlines
                    \draw[thick] (A) -- (B) -- (C) -- (D) -- cycle;
                    \draw[thick] (D) -- (C) -- (V1) -- cycle;
                    \draw[thick] (C) -- (B) -- (V2) -- cycle;
                    \draw[thick] (A) -- (B) -- (V3) -- cycle;
                    \draw[thick] (A) -- (D) -- (V4) -- cycle;

                    % Add labels

                    % Rectangle labels
                    \node[left] at (0,1.5) {3 cm}; % Height of rectangle
                    \node[below] at (2.5,-0.1) {5 cm}; % Width of rectangle

                    % Slanting side lengths of triangles
                    \node[above] at (1,4.8) {6 cm};
                    \node[above] at (4,4.8) {6 cm};
                    \node[right] at (6.2,2.8) {6 cm};
                    \node[right] at (6.2,0) {6 cm};
                    \node[below] at (4,-1.7) {6 cm};
                    \node[below] at (1,-1.7) {6 cm};
                    \node[left] at (-1.8,0.8) {6 cm};
                    \node[left] at (-1.8,2.4) {6 cm};

                    % Vertex Labels
                    \node[above] at (V1) {P};
                    \node[right] at (V2) {P};
                    \node[below] at (V3) {P};
                    \node[left] at (V4) {P};
                    \node[below left ] at (A) {A};
                    \node[below right] at (B) {B};
                    \node[above left ] at (D) {D};
                    \node[above right] at (C) {C};

                \end{tikzpicture}
            </latex-image>
                <shortdescription></shortdescription>
                
            </image>
          <p xml:id="auto_y03g0o8f"> 
             The area of the rectangular base           
            <md>
               <mrow> = \amp \text{length} \times \text{width} </mrow>
                <mrow>= \amp5 \, \text{cm} \times 3 \, \text{cm} </mrow>
                <mrow>= \amp  15 \, \text{cm}^2</mrow>
            </md>
             The height of triangles with base of <m>5 \, \text{cm}</m>
                <md>
                    <mrow>= \amp\sqrt{36-6.25} </mrow>
                    <mrow>= \amp\sqrt{29.75} </mrow>
                    <mrow>= \amp 5.45 \, \text{cm} \, (2 \text{d.p})</mrow>
                </md>
                The area of a triangle with base of 5 cm 
                <md>
                <mrow>= \amp\frac{1}{2}\times \text{base} \times \text{height} </mrow>
                <mrow>= \amp\frac{1}{2} \times 5 \times 5.45  </mrow>
                <mrow>= \amp13.625 \, \text{cm}^2 </mrow>
                </md>
                Since this triangles are two,Therefore total area is:
                <md>
                <mrow>= \amp 2 \times 13.625</mrow>
                <mrow>= \amp27.25 \, \text{cm}^2 </mrow>
                </md>
                The height of triangles with base of 3 cm
                <md>
                 <mrow> = \amp\sqrt{6^2-1.5^2} </mrow>
                 <mrow>= \amp\sqrt{36-2.25} </mrow>
                 <mrow>= \amp\sqrt{33.75} </mrow>
                 <mrow>= \amp5.81 \, \text{cm}^2 (2 \text{d.p}) </mrow>
                 </md>
                 The area of a triangle with base of 3 cm
                 <md>
                 <mrow> = \amp\frac{1}{2}\times \text{base} \times \text{height} </mrow>
                <mrow>= \amp\frac{1}{2} \times 3 \times 5.81  \, \text{cm}^2</mrow>
                <mrow>= \amp 8.715 \, \text{cm}^2 </mrow>
                </md>
                Since this triangles are two,Therefore total area
                <md>
                <mrow>= \amp 2 \times 8.715</mrow>
                <mrow>= \amp17.43 \, \text{cm}^2 </mrow>
                </md>
                Therefore, the surface area of the pyramid is,
                <md>
                <mrow>= \amp15 \, \text{cm}^2 + 27.25 \, \text{cm}^2 + 17.43 \, \text{cm}^2 </mrow>
                <mrow>= \amp59.68 \, \text{cm}^2 </mrow>
               
            </md>
         </p>
        </solution>
    </example>
    <example xml:id="auto_v8jl0xz6">
        <statement>
            <p xml:id="auto_p8lv8c7n">
                Find the surface area of a square pyramid with a height of 6 cm and a side length of 4cm.
            </p>
        </statement>
        <solution>
            
            <p xml:id="auto_kw2t0i6o">
                Select the correct formula and substitute with the given values.
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_l63vo8yu">
                We are given b = 2 by 2 and H = 4, therefore
                <md>
                    <mrow> \text{Surface Area} = \amp \text{Base area} + 4\text{(area of triangles)}  </mrow>
                    <mrow> \text{Base Area} = 2 \, \text{cm} \times 2 \, \text{cm}\amp </mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp 4 \, \text{cm}^2 </mrow>
                    <mrow>\text{Area of one triangle} = \amp \frac{1}{2} b \times h </mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp \frac{1}{2} \times 2 \, \text{cm} \times 4 \, \text{cm} </mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp 4 \, \text{cm}^2 </mrow>
                    <mrow> \text{Area of all triangles}= \amp 4 \, \text{cm}^2 \times 4\, \text{triangles} </mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp 16 \, \text{cm}^2</mrow>
                    <mrow> \text{Surface area}= \amp 16 \, \text{cm}^2 + 4 \, \text{cm}^2</mrow>
                    <mrow> = \amp 20 \, \text{cm}^2 </mrow>
                </md>
            </p>
            <p xml:id="auto_vvx3kgig">
                The surface area for the square pyramid is <m>20 \, \text{cm}^2</m>.
            </p>
        </solution>
           
    </example>

