    <axiom component="lesson-plan">
        <title>Differentiation</title>
        <table xml:id="auto_n6lrhnj8">
            <title>Differentiation Strategies</title>
            <tabular halign="left">
                <row header="yes" bottom="minor">
                    <cell>Learner Group</cell>
                    <cell>Strategy &amp; Learning Experience</cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>Struggling Learners (Support)</cell>
                    <cell>
                        <line><alert>Scaffolding:</alert> Provide pre-drawn pyramid nets for students to cut and fold. Use square pyramids with simple dimensions for initial practice. Pair struggling students with confident problem solvers. Provide step-by-step calculation templates. Break down the formula into steps: Find base area, find area of one triangular face, multiply by number of faces, add.</line>
                    </cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>On-Level Learners (Core)</cell>
                    <cell>
                        <line>The core lesson activities as described above. Encourage students to verify their formula with different pyramid types and explain the difference between a pyramid and a prism.</line>
                    </cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                </row>
                <row>
                    <cell>Advanced Learners (Challenge)</cell>
                    <cell>
                        <line><alert>Extended Learning Experience:</alert> Derive the formula for triangular pyramids using Heron's formula. Explore real-world applications: Egyptian pyramids, tent roofs, food containers. Investigate problems where the slant height must be calculated using Pythagorean theorem. Apply the concept to composite solids involving pyramids.</line>
                    </cell>
                    <cell></cell>
                </row>
            </tabular>
        </table>
        <paragraphs>
            <title>Extension Activity</title>
            <p xml:id="auto_ff5fh740">
                <alert>Real-World Application:</alert> Identify pyramid-shaped objects around school or home (e.g., tent, roof, food container, toys). Measure the dimensions of each object or use estimated values. Calculate the surface area of each object using the pyramid formula. Compare results with classmates and discuss any differences. Present findings with diagrams, measurements, and calculations.
            </p>
        </paragraphs>
    </axiom>
    <xi:include href="../../resources-assessment.ptx" />
    <xi:include href="../../resources-reflection.ptx"/>
</subsection>